Shifting Attitudes Toward Vaccines on Twitter During COVID-19
Course: Textual Data Analysis in R
Date: April 2026
Tags: R Text Analysis Sentiment Analysis Social Media Public Health Data Cleaning Data Visualization NLP Research Project Data Science
In this group research project, we studied how vaccine-related sentiment changed on Twitter during 2021 of the COVID-19 pandemic. We worked with a large public tweet dataset and cleaned the data in R by filtering for vaccine-related posts, removing duplicates, retweets, and spam-like content, and keeping key variables such as date, follower count, and retweet count. We then used a customized AFINN sentiment dictionary with added vaccine-specific terms to measure tweet sentiment over time. Our analysis showed that positive tweets were more common than negative tweets overall, and sentiment did not become steadily more negative over the year. We also looked at tweet volume over time and tested whether sentiment was related to follower count or retweet count. This project helped me build experience in data cleaning, text analysis, sentiment scoring, and presenting findings through written reports and visualizations.

