Understanding Offensive Success in NCAA Lacrosse Through Possession-Level Analysis
Course: Sports Analytics
Date: April 2026
Tags: R Sports Analytics Data Analysis Statistical Modeling Logistic Regression Data Cleaning Data Visualization Hypothesis Testing Research Project Data Science
In this project, my group and I collected and analyzed 205 NCAA lacrosse possessions to study what makes an offense more likely to create a shot or score. Instead of only using box score stats, we tracked possession-level details like how the possession started, time in transition, time on offense, passes, dodges, shot type, and shot location. We then used summary statistics, t-tests, chi-square tests, and logistic regression in R to find which possession features were most related to offensive success. One of our main findings was that possessions ending in a shot tended to involve more passes after the offense got settled and more dodges, while possessions with more transition passing were more likely to end in turnovers. We also found that shot location mattered more than shot type when looking at which shots became goals.

